{"badges":["TM5","TM6"],"preparations":[{"content":["Line a baking tray (30 cm x 40 cm) with baking paper.","Place mahlepi, mastic gum (if using) and 100 g sugar in mixing bowl then grind <nobr>1 min\/speed 10<\/nobr>. Transfer to a bowl and set aside.","Place milk, remaining 5 g sugar, yeast and 3 eggs in mixing bowl then heat <nobr>4 min\/37°C\/speed 2<\/nobr>.","Add flour, butter, salt and reserved sugar mixture then knead <nobr>3 min\/<\/nobr>. Dough will be sticky. Transfer dough to a well-floured surface and shape into a ball. Place dough ball in a bowl, cover with a tea towel and leave in a warm place until doubled in size (approx. 1 hour).","Divide dough into 3 pieces and roll each piece into a long rope (approx. 40 cm). Join the 3 ropes at one end, plait them together, and join again at the other end. Place plait on prepared tray and brush with 1 beaten egg. Decorate with flaked almonds (if using) and leave to rise for 10 minutes.","Place into cold oven, turn oven temperature to 180°C and bake for 35-45 minutes (180°C) until golden brown. Leave to cool slightly before serving."]}],"ingredients":[{"title":"","content":["1 tsp mahlepi seeds (see tip)","3 pieces mastic gum (see tip) (optional)","105 g sugar","100 g milk","2 tsp dried instant yeast (see tip)","4 medium eggs, 1 beaten for glazing","450 g plain flour, plus extra for dusting","70 g unsalted butter, soft","1 pinch fine sea salt","flaked almonds, for decorating (optional)"]}],"id":"r351528","imageLink":"https:\/\/2.bp.blogspot.com\/-Ns_1e86urUg\/XZam5z-d-UI\/AAAAAAAAg3Q\/UUFJtfJzp6AT7DvpkZIpQmnRL6sd5HH5wCLcBGAsYHQ\/s1600\/0_-MHWan2r78aYObQ5.png","title":"Greek Easter Bread (Tsoureki)","publishedAt":"2018-07-02T00:00:00Z","nutrition":{"protein":"7 g","fat":"7 g","uom":"per 1 portion","carbohydrates":"38 g","calories":"1023 kJ \/ 243 kcal"},"usefulItems":"tea towel, pastry brush, baking tray (30 cm x 40 cm), baking paper, oven","hintsAndTricks":["Mehlepi (also called mahlab) is an aromatic spice made from cherry seeds, which are ground to a powder. It's often used in traditional Greek Christmas and Easter dishes. It can be found in speciality food stores, spice stores or online. Alternatively, substitute with fennel seeds or cardamom.","Mastiha, or mastic gum, is a crystal, resinous spice and natural chewing gum. It is often used in bread-making in Greek bread recipes. It can be found in speciality food stores or online. If not available, add <nobr>½ tsp<\/nobr> vanilla extract in <nobr>step 4<\/nobr> instead."],"basicInfo":["medium","15m","2h 20m","12 portions"]}